      {
        "title": "Autopsy Digital Forensics: Complete Structured Guide",
        "content": "# Autopsy Digital Forensics: Complete Structured Guide\n\n## 1. Installation & Case Management\n\n### What it is / Why it matters\nAutopsy is an open-source digital forensics platform that provides a GUI-based interface for comprehensive media analysis. Proper case management ensures evidence integrity and organized investigations.\n\n### Step-by-step commands\n```bash\nInstallation on Linux\nsudo apt update\nsudo apt install autopsy\n\nInstallation on Windows\nDownload from sleuthkit.org/autopsy\njava -jar autopsy-4.19.0.zip\n\nLaunch Autopsy\nsudo autopsy\nAccess via http://localhost:9999/autopsy\n```\n\n### What to expect\n```\nAutopsy startup:\nStarting web server on port 9999\nOpening browser to http://localhost:9999/autopsy\nCase management interface loads\n```\n\n### Troubleshooting & tips\n- **Java issues**: Ensure Java 8+ is installed\n- **Permission errors**: Run as administrator/root when necessary\n- **Port conflicts**: Change default port with `--http-port 8888`\n\n### Safety / ethics note\nOnly analyze media you own or have legal authority to examine. Maintain chain of custody for all evidence.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Case Creation & Evidence Ingestion\n\n### What it is / Why it matters\nProper case setup and evidence ingestion ensure data integrity, metadata preservation, and organized analysis workflows.\n\n### Step-by-step commands\n```\n1. Click \"New Case\"\n2. Case Name: \"Investigation_20231015\"\n3. Base Directory: /cases/\n4. Add Evidence → Disk Image or Local Disk\n5. Select image file (dd/raw, E01, AFF)\n6. Configure ingest modules:\n   - Recent Activity\n   - Hash Lookup\n   - File Type Identification\n   - EXIF Metadata\n   - Email Parser\n   - Keyword Search\n```\n\n### What to expect\n```\nCase creation:\nCase: Investigation_20231015 created\nEvidence: device_image.dd added (500GB)\nIngest modules: 8 modules configured\nProcessing: 2-8 hours depending on size\n```\n\n### Troubleshooting & tips\n- **Large images**: Process in stages, enable only needed modules\n- **Corrupt images**: Verify image integrity with `fsstat` first\n- **Encrypted volumes**: Note encryption for later analysis\n\n---\n\n## 3. File System Analysis & Timeline\n\n### What it is / Why it matters\nFile system analysis reconstructs directory structures, while timeline analysis creates chronological event sequences crucial for incident reconstruction.\n\n### Step-by-step commands\n```\n1. Navigate to \"Data Sources\" tab\n2. Expand file system tree\n3. View \"File Types\" for categorization\n4. Access \"Timeline\" interface\n5. Configure time range filters\n6. Export timeline for external analysis\n\n# Filter examples:\nExtension: .exe,.dll,.bat\nDate Range: Last 30 days\nFile Size: >1MB\n```\n\n### What to expect\n```\nFile system view:\n/ (Root)\n├── /Windows/System32/\n├── /Users/John/Documents/\n├── /$Recycle.Bin/\n└── /Program Files/\n\nTimeline output:\n2023-10-15 14:23:01 | FILE MODIFIED | C:\\Windows\\malware.exe\n2023-10-15 14:23:05 | FILE ACCESS    | C:\\Users\\John\\documents\\secret.pdf\n```\n\n### Troubleshooting & tips\n- **Time zones**: Adjust for correct local time\n- **MAC times**: Understand Modified, Accessed, Created differences\n- **File system artifacts**: Check $MFT, $LogFile for NTFS\n\n---\n\n## 4. Keyword Searching & Indexing\n\n### What it is / Why it matters\nKeyword searching locates specific text patterns across entire media, while indexing accelerates searches and enables complex pattern matching.\n\n### Step-by-step commands\n```\n1. Go to \"Keywords\" tab\n2. Add keyword lists:\n   - Credit card numbers\n   - Email addresses\n   - Phone numbers\n   - Custom regex patterns\n3. Configure search scope:\n   - All files\n   - Specific extensions\n   - Unallocated space\n4. Run \"Indexed Search\"\n5. Review results in \"Results\" view\n```\n\n### What to expect\n```\nKeyword search results:\nPattern: Credit Card\nMatches: 12 files, 45 instances\nFiles: \n  - secret.txt (3 matches)\n  - finances.xlsx (8 matches)\n  - unallocated (34 matches)\n\nIndexing progress:\nIndexed: 450,000 files\nRemaining: 15,000 files\nEstimated: 45 minutes\n```\n\n### Troubleshooting & tips\n- **Performance**: Index overnight for large datasets\n- **False positives**: Refine regex patterns\n- **Encoding issues**: Specify correct character encoding\n\n---\n\n## 5. Hash Analysis & Alerting\n\n### What it is / Why it matters\nHash analysis identifies known files (whitelist/blacklist), detects duplicates, and flags suspicious or known-malicious files.\n\n### Step-by-step commands\n```\n1. Navigate to \"Hash Lookup\" ingest module\n2. Import hash sets:\n   - NSRL (known good files)\n   - NIST malware hashes\n   - Custom hash sets\n3. Configure hash alert rules:\n   - Alert on known bad hashes\n   - Ignore known good hashes\n   - Flag unknown executables\n4. Review \"Hash Hit\" results\n```\n\n### What to expect\n```\nHash analysis results:\nTotal files: 250,000\nKnown good: 240,000 (96%)\nKnown bad: 15 (0.006%)\nUnknown: 9,985 (3.994%)\n\nAlerts:\nCRITICAL: malware.exe matches known malware hash\nSUSPICIOUS: unknown_device_driver.sys\n```\n\n### Troubleshooting & tips\n- **Hash set management**: Keep hash databases updated\n- **False negatives**: Use multiple hash algorithms when possible\n- **Performance**: Pre-filter by file type before hashing\n\n---\n\n## 6. EXIF & Metadata Analysis\n\n### What it is / Why it matters\nEXIF and metadata analysis extracts hidden information from files, revealing creation details, authorship, and potential evidence of manipulation.\n\n### Step-by-step commands\n```\n1. Enable \"EXIF Parser\" ingest module\n2. Filter by file types:\n   - Images: .jpg, .png, .tiff\n   - Documents: .pdf, .docx, .pptx\n   - Videos: .mp4, .avi, .mov\n3. Review metadata in \"EXIF\" results tab\n4. Search for specific metadata:\n   - GPS coordinates\n   - Camera model\n   - Author information\n   - Software versions\n```\n\n### What to expect\n```\nEXIF results:\nFile: vacation.jpg\n- Camera: Canon EOS 5D Mark IV\n- GPS: 40.7128° N, 74.0060° W\n- Date: 2023-10-15 14:23:01\n- Software: Adobe Photoshop 2023\n\nMetadata alerts:\nDOCUMENT: resume.docx contains \"Track Changes\"\nPDF: confidential.pdf contains \"Form Fields\"\n```\n\n### Troubleshooting & tips\n- **Metadata stripping**: Some tools remove metadata intentionally\n- **Time zones**: EXIF dates may use different timezone formats\n- **Corrupt metadata**: Files may have incomplete headers\n\n---\n\n## 7. Email & Communication Analysis\n\n### What it is / Why it matters\nEmail analysis extracts and reconstructs communication patterns, attachments, and conversation threads important for investigations.\n\n### Step-by-step commands\n```\n1. Enable \"Email Parser\" ingest module\n2. Configure email sources:\n   - PST files\n   - MBOX files\n   - EML files\n   - Outlook profiles\n3. Review in \"Email Messages\" tab\n4. Search email content:\n   - Specific senders/recipients\n   - Date ranges\n   - Attachment types\n   - Keywords in body\n```\n\n### What to expect\n```\nEmail analysis:\nAccounts found: 3\nMessages processed: 15,234\nAttachments: 345\n\nResults:\nSender: john@company.com → admin@target.com\nSubject: \"Urgent: Financial Documents\"\nAttachment: malware.zip (flagged)\nDate: 2023-10-15 14:23:01\n```\n\n### Troubleshooting & tips\n- **Large PST files**: Process in segments to avoid memory issues\n- **Encrypted emails**: Note password protection for later analysis\n- **Character encoding**: Handle international character sets properly\n\n---\n\n## 8. Web Artifact Analysis\n\n### What it is / Why it matters\nWeb artifact analysis reconstructs browsing history, downloads, cookies, and form data revealing user behavior and potential malicious activity.\n\n### Step-by-step commands\n```\n1. Enable \"Recent Activity\" ingest module\n2. Configure browser parsing:\n   - Chrome history\n   - Firefox profiles\n   - Internet Explorer cache\n   - Safari data\n3. Review in \"Web History\" tab\n4. Analyze downloads, bookmarks, cookies\n5. Export browsing timeline\n```\n\n### What to expect\n```\nWeb artifacts:\nBrowser: Chrome\nHistory entries: 12,456\nDownloads: 234\nCookies: 8,923\n\nNotable findings:\nURL: http://malicious.com/download.exe\nDownload: 2023-10-15 14:23:01\nFilename: \"update.exe\" (actually malware.exe)\n```\n\n### Troubleshooting & tips\n- **Browser versions**: Different versions store data differently\n- **Private browsing**: Limited artifacts in incognito mode\n- **Cloud sync**: Modern browsers sync across devices\n\n---\n\n## 9. Registry & System Artifact Analysis\n\n### What it is / Why it matters\nWindows Registry analysis reveals system configuration, user activity, program execution, and persistence mechanisms used by malware.\n\n### Step-by-step commands\n```\n1. Enable \"Registry Parser\" in ingest modules\n2. Automatically extracts:\n   - User hives (NTUSER.DAT)\n   - System hives (SYSTEM, SOFTWARE, SAM)\n   - USB device history\n   - Program execution\n   - Recent documents\n3. Review in \"Registry Keys\" results\n4. Search for specific keys/values\n```\n\n### What to expect\n```\nRegistry findings:\nUSB Devices: 15 devices connected\n  - SanDisk Cruzer (Serial: 4C530000000000000000)\n  - Last connected: 2023-10-15\n\nProgram Execution:\n- malware.exe: 45 executions\n- cmd.exe: 128 executions\n\nUser Activity:\nRecent documents: secret.pdf, finances.xlsx\n```\n\n### Troubleshooting & tips\n- **Registry corruption**: Some hives may be incomplete\n- **Timestomping**: Malware may alter registry timestamps\n- **Volume shadow copies**: Check VSS for historical registry data\n\n---\n\n## 10. Reporting & Evidence Export\n\n### What it is / Why it matters\nComprehensive reporting documents findings, supports legal proceedings, and enables stakeholder communication while maintaining evidence integrity.\n\n### Step-by-step commands\n```\n1. Navigate to \"Generate Report\" feature\n2. Select report format:\n   - HTML (interactive)\n   - PDF (printable)\n   - Excel (data analysis)\n3. Choose report sections:\n   - Executive Summary\n   - Analysis Details\n   - Artifact Lists\n   - Timeline\n   - Supporting Evidence\n4. Configure evidence export:\n   - Export specific files\n   - Create logical copies\n   - Generate integrity hashes\n```\n\n### What to expect\n```\nReport generation:\nProcessing: 15 minutes\nSections: 8 sections included\nFiles: 245 artifacts referenced\nSize: 45MB total\n\nExport results:\nExported: 15 files for evidence\nHashes: SHA-256 generated\nChain of custody: Documented\n```\n\n### Troubleshooting & tips\n- **Report size**: Split large reports by category\n- **Sensitive data**: Redact PII before distribution\n- **Format compatibility**: Test reports on target systems\n\n### Safety / ethics note\nAll reports must maintain factual accuracy, avoid speculation, and protect sensitive personal information. Follow legal requirements for evidence handling and privacy protection.\n\n---\n\n## Quick Reference - Critical Modules\n\n```\nEssential Ingest Modules:\n✓ Recent Activity    - Browser history, downloads\n✓ Hash Lookup       - Known file identification  \n✓ File Type         - Extension vs content analysis\n✓ EXIF Parser       - Metadata extraction\n✓ Email Parser      - Communication analysis\n✓ Keyword Search    - Pattern matching\n✓ Registry Parser   - Windows artifact analysis\n\nKey Analysis Tabs:\n▶ Data Sources - File system navigation\n▶ Results      - Ingest module findings\n▶ Timeline     - Chronological event view\n▶ Keywords     - Search configuration\n▶ Tags         - Evidence organization\n```\n\nThis structured Autopsy guide provides comprehensive digital forensics capabilities while maintaining legal and ethical standards for professional investigations."
      }
