      {
        "title": "Python Basic",
        "content": "# **HOW TO RUN PYTHON SCRIPTS: COMPLETE GUIDE**\n\n## **METHOD 1: RUNNING FROM COMMAND LINE (RECOMMENDED)**\n\n### **Step-by-Step Guide:**\n\n**Step 1: Open Command Line Interface**\n- **Windows:** Press `Windows Key + R`, type `cmd`, press Enter\n- **Mac:** Press `Command + Space`, type `terminal`, press Enter\n- **Linux:** Press `Ctrl + Alt + T`\n\n**Step 2: Navigate to Script Location**\n```bash\n# Check current directory\npwd\n\n# Navigate to Desktop (if script is on Desktop)\ncd Desktop\n\n# List files to see your script\ndir      # Windows\nls       # Mac/Linux\n```\n\n**Step 3: Run the Script**\n```bash\n# Basic run command\npython script_name.py\n\n# If python doesn't work, try:\npython3 script_name.py\n\n# If you get \"python not found\", install Python first\n```\n\n---\n\n## **METHOD 2: RUNNING IN VS CODE (EASIEST FOR BEGINNERS)**\n\n### **Step-by-Step:**\n\n**Step 1: Install VS Code**\n1. Go to https://code.visualstudio.com/\n2. Download and install\n3. Open VS Code\n\n**Step 2: Create/Open Your Script**\n```bash\n# Create new file\n1. Click \"File\" → \"New File\"\n2. Copy-paste your Python code\n3. Save as: `my_script.py`\n\n# OR open existing file\n1. Click \"File\" → \"Open File\"\n2. Navigate to your .py file\n```\n\n**Step 3: Install Python Extension**\n1. Click Extensions icon (square icon on left)\n2. Search for \"Python\"\n3. Install \"Python\" extension by Microsoft\n\n**Step 4: Run Your Script**\n```bash\n# Method A: Click Run button\n1. Click \"Run\" menu\n2. Select \"Run Without Debugging\"\n3. Or press F5\n\n# Method B: Use Terminal in VS Code\n1. Click \"Terminal\" → \"New Terminal\"\n2. Type: python my_script.py\n3. Press Enter\n\n# Method C: Right-click method\n1. Right-click in editor\n2. Select \"Run Python File in Terminal\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## **METHOD 3: RUNNING IN IDLE (Python's Built-in Editor)**\n\n**Step 1: Open IDLE**\n- **Windows:** Start Menu → Python → IDLE\n- **Mac/Linux:** Open Terminal → type `idle`\n\n**Step 2: Create/Run Script**\n```python\n# Create new file:\n1. File → New File\n2. Type your code\n3. Save as: hack_script.py\n\n# Run script:\n1. Press F5\n2. Or: Run → Run Module\n```\n\n---\n\n## **PRACTICAL EXAMPLES: RUNNING SECURITY SCRIPTS**\n\n### **Example 1: Network Scanner**\n```bash\n# 1. Save script as 'network_scanner.py'\n# 2. Open Command Prompt/Terminal\n# 3. Navigate to script location\ncd Downloads\n\n# 4. Run with Python\npython network_scanner.py\n\n# Expected output if successful:\n# ============================================================\n# NETWORK DEVICE SCANNER\n# ============================================================\n# [*] Your IP: 192.168.1.105\n# [*] Scanning network: 192.168.1.0/24\n```\n\n### **Example 2: Password Checker**\n```bash\n# 1. Save as 'password_check.py'\n# 2. Run it:\npython password_check.py\n\n# 3. When prompted, enter a password\n# Output shows security analysis\n```\n\n### **Example 3: Port Scanner**\n```bash\n# Run port scanner (local testing only!)\npython port_scanner.py\n\n# Output shows open ports on localhost\n```\n\n---\n\n## **TROUBLESHOOTING COMMON ERRORS**\n\n### **Error 1: \"python is not recognized\"**\n**Solution:**\n```bash\n# Windows - Reinstall Python with PATH option checked\n1. Download Python from python.org\n2. During install, CHECK \"Add Python to PATH\"\n3. Re-open Command Prompt\n\n# Mac/Linux - Install Python\nbrew install python3      # Mac with Homebrew\nsudo apt install python3  # Linux Ubuntu\n```\n\n### **Error 2: \"Module not found\"**\n**Solution:**\n```bash\n# Install missing module\npip install module_name\n\n# Example for nmap scanner:\npip install python-nmap\n\n# If pip not found:\npython -m pip install module_name\n```\n\n### **Error 3: \"Permission denied\"**\n**Solution:**\n```bash\n# Linux/Mac - Use sudo\nsudo python script.py\n\n# Windows - Run as Administrator\n1. Right-click Command Prompt\n2. Select \"Run as administrator\"\n3. Navigate to script and run\n```\n\n---\n\n## **COMPLETE WORKFLOW EXAMPLE**\n\n### **From Start to Finish: Network Scanner**\n\n**Step 1: Create the Script File**\n```python\n# Open Notepad (Windows) or TextEdit (Mac)\n# Copy this simple scanner:\n\nimport socket\n\ndef simple_port_scanner():\n    print(\"Simple Port Scanner\")\n    target = \"127.0.0.1\"  # Localhost only!\n    ports = [21, 22, 80, 443]\n    \n    for port in ports:\n        sock = socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_STREAM)\n        sock.settimeout(1)\n        result = sock.connect_ex((target, port))\n        \n        if result == 0:\n            print(f\"Port {port}: OPEN\")\n        else:\n            print(f\"Port {port}: CLOSED\")\n        sock.close()\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    simple_port_scanner()\n\n# Save as: simple_scanner.py\n```\n\n**Step 2: Open Terminal/Command Prompt**\n```bash\n# Windows: Press Win+R, type \"cmd\"\n# Mac: Command+Space, type \"terminal\"\n```\n\n**Step 3: Navigate and Run**\n```bash\n# If saved on Desktop:\ncd Desktop\n\n# Run the script:\npython simple_scanner.py\n```\n\n**Expected Output:**\n```\nSimple Port Scanner\nPort 21: CLOSED\nPort 22: CLOSED\nPort 80: CLOSED\nPort 443: CLOSED\n```\n\n---\n\n## **QUICK REFERENCE: COMMON COMMANDS**\n\n| Task | Command | Example |\n|------|---------|---------|\n| Check Python version | `python --version` | `python --version` |\n| Install module | `pip install module` | `pip install requests` |\n| List installed | `pip list` | `pip list` |\n| Run script | `python file.py` | `python scanner.py` |\n| Navigate up | `cd ..` | `cd ..` |\n| Navigate to folder | `cd foldername` | `cd Desktop` |\n| List files | `dir` (Win) / `ls` (Mac/Linux) | `ls` |\n| Clear screen | `cls` (Win) / `clear` (Mac/Linux) | `clear` |\n\n---\n\n## **PRO TIPS FOR BEGINNERS**\n\n1. **Always test first with localhost (127.0.0.1)**\n2. **Save scripts with .py extension** (important!)\n3. **Use print() to debug** - add `print(\"Step 1 complete\")` to track progress\n4. **Run in steps** - test small parts before running full script\n5. **Keep terminal open** while working - saves time\n\n### **Practice Exercise:**\n```bash\n# 1. Create test.py with this content:\nprint(\"Hello, Cybersecurity!\")\nprint(\"My first script is running!\")\n\n# 2. Save it\n# 3. Open terminal\n# 4. Navigate to file location\n# 5. Run: python test.py\n\n# Expected output:\nHello, Cybersecurity!\nMy first script is running!\n```\n\n---\n\n## **SAFETY WARNING**\n\n**ONLY RUN SCRIPTS ON:**\n- Your own computer\n- Virtual machines you own\n- Authorized test environments\n- Localhost (127.0.0.1)\n\n**NEVER RUN ON:**\n- Other people's networks\n- Work/school networks without permission\n- Websites you don't own\n- Public networks\n\n**Remember:** Running security tools without permission is **illegal** and **unethical**. Use these skills to protect, not attack.\n\n---\n"
      }
