      {
        "title": "Wireshark Complete Lab Guide",
        "content": "\n# Wireshark Complete Lab Guide — Detailed Commands & Examples\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\n**Wireshark** is a free, open-source network protocol analyzer for capturing and analyzing traffic.  \nIt is widely used for network troubleshooting, cybersecurity, malware investigation, and protocol development.\n\n**Safety / ethics:**  \nOnly capture traffic on networks you are authorized to monitor.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Installation & Setup\n\n### 2.1 Windows\n```powershell\n# Download Wireshark installer\n# Run as Administrator\n# Install Npcap (packet capture driver) when prompted\n```\n\n### 2.2 Linux\n```bash\n# Ubuntu / Debian\nsudo apt update && sudo apt install wireshark\n\n# CentOS / RHEL\nsudo yum install wireshark\n\n# Add user to capture group\nsudo usermod -a -G wireshark $USER\n```\n\n**Tip:** Log out and log in again for group permissions to take effect.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Starting Wireshark\n\n### 3.1 GUI Mode\n1. Open Wireshark.\n2. Select the interface (Ethernet/Wi-Fi).\n3. Start capture: shark fin icon or `Ctrl+E`.\n4. Stop capture: red square icon.\n\n**Interface Overview:**\n- **Packet List Pane:** Summary of packets\n- **Packet Details Pane:** Protocol hierarchy\n- **Packet Bytes Pane:** Hex/ASCII raw data\n\n**Tip:** Apply filters to reduce capture size.\n\n---\n\n### 3.2 CLI Mode — TShark\n\n#### List Interfaces\n```bash\ntshark -D\n# Output Example:\n# 1. enp0s3\n# 2. wlan0\n```\n\n#### Capture Packets\n```bash\n# Capture live packets on interface 1\ntshark -i 1\n\n# Capture only 50 packets\ntshark -i 1 -c 50\n\n# Capture and save to file\ntshark -i 1 -w mycapture.pcap\n\n# Read capture file\ntshark -r mycapture.pcap\n```\n\n#### Live Example\n```bash\ntshark -i 1 -c 10\n# Output:\n# 1 0.000000 192.168.1.100 → 192.168.1.1 TCP 74 443 → 53764 [SYN] Seq=0 Win=64240\n# 2 0.001234 192.168.1.1 → 192.168.1.100 TCP 74 53764 → 443 [SYN, ACK] Seq=0 Ack=1\n```\n\n**Tip:** Use `sudo` if non-root cannot access interface.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Capture Filters (BPF)\n\n**Purpose:** Reduce unnecessary traffic during capture.\n\n```bash\n# Capture only HTTP\ntshark -i 1 -f \"port 80\"\n\n# Capture specific host\ntshark -i 1 -f \"host 192.168.1.1\"\n\n# Capture subnet\ntshark -i 1 -f \"net 192.168.1.0/24\"\n\n# Capture TCP only\ntshark -i 1 -f \"tcp\"\n\n# Capture multiple ports\ntshark -i 1 -f \"port 80 or port 443\"\n\n# Exclude SSH\ntshark -i 1 -f \"not port 22\"\n```\n\n**Live Example:**  \n```bash\ntshark -i 1 -f \"tcp port 80\" -c 5\n# Output:\n# 1 0.000000 192.168.1.100 → 93.184.216.34 TCP 74 53764 → 80 [SYN] Seq=0 Win=64240\n# 2 0.001200 93.184.216.34 → 192.168.1.100 TCP 74 80 → 53764 [SYN, ACK] Seq=0 Ack=1\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Display Filters\n\n**Purpose:** Refine which packets are visible after capture.\n\n### Common Filters\n```text\nhttp                 # HTTP\ntls or ssl           # HTTPS\ndns                  # DNS queries\ntcp.port == 80       # TCP 80\nudp                  # UDP packets\n```\n\n### IP Filters\n```text\nip.addr == 192.168.1.1\nip.src == 192.168.1.100\nip.dst == 8.8.8.8\nip.addr == 192.168.1.0/24\n```\n\n### Advanced Filters\n```text\nhttp.request.method == \"GET\"\nhttp.response.code == 404\ntcp.flags.syn == 1\nframe.len > 1000\nhttp and ip.addr == 192.168.1.1\ntcp.port == 80 or tcp.port == 443\n```\n\n**TShark CLI Example:**\n```bash\ntshark -r mycapture.pcap -Y \"http.request.method==POST\"\n```\n\n**Live Output:**\n```text\n1 0.123456 192.168.1.100 → 93.184.216.34 HTTP POST /login HTTP/1.1\n2 0.124000 93.184.216.34 → 192.168.1.100 HTTP/1.1 200 OK\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Analysis Techniques\n\n### Follow TCP Stream\n**GUI:** Right-click packet → Follow → TCP Stream  \n**CLI:**\n```bash\ntshark -r mycapture.pcap -z follow,tcp,ascii,0\n```\n\n**Example Output:**\n```text\nGET /index.html HTTP/1.1\nHost: example.com\nUser-Agent: Mozilla/5.0\n```\n\n### Statistics\n- **Protocol Hierarchy:** `Statistics → Protocol Hierarchy`  \n- **Conversations:** `Statistics → Conversations`  \n- **I/O Graphs:** `Statistics → I/O Graphs`  \n- **Expert Info:** `Analyze → Expert Information`\n\n**CLI Examples:**\n```bash\n# Protocol hierarchy\ntshark -r mycapture.pcap -q -z io,phs\n\n# TCP conversations\ntshark -r mycapture.pcap -q -z conv,tcp\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Security & Forensics\n\n### Malware / Suspicious Traffic\n```text\ndns and dns.flags.response == 0\nhttp.request.method == \"POST\"\ntcp.port > 1024 and tcp.port < 65535\nframe contains \"base64\"\n```\n\n### Security Checks\n- Unencrypted credentials (HTTP auth, FTP, Telnet)  \n- Suspicious file downloads (HTTP/FTP)  \n- Port scanning (TCP SYN multiple ports)  \n- DDoS analysis (packet rate / IP frequency)\n\n**CLI Example:**\n```bash\ntshark -r mycapture.pcap -Y \"tcp.flags.syn==1\" -T fields -e ip.src -e tcp.dstport\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Pro Tips\n\n- Use capture filters (`-f`) to reduce load.  \n- Save often; large captures consume memory.  \n- Color rules for protocol highlighting.  \n- Time display format adjustments.  \n- Export HTTP/FTP objects (`File → Export Objects`).  \n- Decrypt TLS using server keys if available.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Common Use Cases\n\n- **Network Troubleshooting:** Latency, connectivity, app traffic.  \n- **Security Analysis:** Malware, attack detection, incident response.  \n- **Data Forensics:** Investigate exfiltration, suspicious communications.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Advanced TShark Commands\n\n```bash\n# Verbose capture\ntshark -i 1 -V\n\n# Capture 60 seconds, save to file\ntshark -i 1 -a duration:60 -w output.pcap\n\n# Read file with filter\ntshark -r output.pcap -Y \"http.request.method==POST\"\n\n# TCP conversations summary\ntshark -r output.pcap -q -z conv,tcp\n\n# Protocol hierarchy\ntshark -r output.pcap -q -z io,phs\n\n# Follow TCP stream ASCII\ntshark -r output.pcap -z follow,tcp,ascii,0\n\n# Capture SSH port only\ntshark -i 1 -f \"port 22\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## References\n- [Wireshark Official](https://www.wireshark.org/)  \n- [TShark Manual](https://www.wireshark.org/docs/man-pages/tshark.html)  \n- [Wireshark Display Filters](https://www.wireshark.org/docs/dfref/)\n"
      },
      {
        "title": "🕵️ Wireshark Cheat Sheet",
        "content": "Here's a **clean, practical, and easy-to-use Wireshark Cheat Sheet**—organized by real-world tasks, with live examples and quick-reference syntax for network analysis and security investigations.\n\n---\n\n# 🕵️ **Wireshark Cheat Sheet**  \n*Capture, analyze, and troubleshoot network traffic like a pro.*\n\n---\n\n## 🧰 **1. Getting Started**\n\n| Action | How To |\n|-------|--------|\n| **Start Capture** | Click on a network interface (e.g., `eth0`, `Wi-Fi`) in the main window. |\n| **Stop Capture** | Click the red ■ (Stop) button. |\n| **Save Capture** | `File → Save As` → `.pcapng` (recommended) or `.pcap`. |\n| **Open Capture** | `File → Open` or drag `.pcap` file into Wireshark. |\n\n> ✅ **Pro Tip**: Run Wireshark as **non-root** using `dumpcap` permissions (set during install on Linux).\n\n---\n\n## 🔍 **2. Display Filters (Applied *After* Capture)**  \n*Type in the filter bar at the top.*\n\n### 🔹 **Basic Filters**\n| Filter | Purpose |\n|-------|--------|\n| `ip.addr == 192.168.1.10` | All traffic to/from this IP |\n| `ip.src == 10.0.0.5` | Only packets **from** this IP |\n| `ip.dst == 8.8.8.8` | Only packets **to** this IP |\n| `tcp.port == 443` | HTTPS traffic (TCP) |\n| `udp.port == 53` | DNS traffic (UDP) |\n| `http` | All HTTP traffic |\n| `dns` | DNS queries/responses |\n| `icmp` | Ping (ICMP) packets |\n| `arp` | Address Resolution Protocol traffic |\n| `tls` or `ssl` | Encrypted TLS/SSL sessions |\n\n### 🔹 **Advanced Filters**\n| Filter | Purpose |\n|-------|--------|\n| `http.request.method == \"POST\"` | HTTP POST requests |\n| `http.response.code == 200` | Successful HTTP responses |\n| `http contains \"password\"` | Search for “password” in HTTP payloads |\n| `tcp.flags.syn == 1 and tcp.flags.ack == 0` | New TCP connections (SYN only) |\n| `tcp.stream eq 12` | View all packets in TCP stream #12 |\n| `frame.len > 1500` | Packets larger than standard MTU (possible fragmentation or tunneling) |\n| `ip.ttl < 10` | Suspiciously low TTL (possible tunneling or spoofing) |\n\n### 🔹 **Filter Operators**\n| Operator | Meaning |\n|--------|--------|\n| `==` | Equal |\n| `!=` | Not equal |\n| `>` / `<` | Greater/less than |\n| `>=` / `<=` | Greater/less than or equal |\n| `&&` or `and` | Logical AND |\n| `||` or `or` | Logical OR |\n| `!` or `not` | Negation |\n\n> 💡 **Shortcut**: Right-click any field in **Packet Details** → **Apply as Filter**.\n\n---\n\n## 🎯 **3. Capture Filters (BPF Syntax – Applied *Before* Capture)**  \n*Set via “Capture → Options → Capture Filter”*\n\n> ⚠️ Uses **Berkeley Packet Filter (BPF)** syntax – **no spaces around `==`**, and **different keywords**.\n\n| Filter | Purpose |\n|-------|--------|\n| `host 192.168.1.1` | Traffic to/from this IP |\n| `net 10.0.0.0/24` | All traffic in subnet |\n| `port 22` | All SSH traffic (TCP or UDP) |\n| `tcp port 80` | Only TCP on port 80 |\n| `udp port 53` | Only DNS (UDP) |\n| `not arp` | Exclude ARP (reduces noise) |\n| `host 192.168.1.10 and port 443` | Traffic to/from host on HTTPS |\n| `ether host aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:ff` | Filter by MAC address |\n\n> ❌ **Not allowed**: `http`, `dns` — these are **display filters only** (require protocol dissection).\n\n---\n\n## 🔗 **4. Following Streams (Reconstruct Conversations)**\n\n1. Right-click any **TCP** or **UDP** packet.\n2. Go to **Follow → TCP Stream** (or **UDP Stream**).\n3. View full client/server conversation in plain text (e.g., HTTP headers, chat messages, API calls).\n\n> 📌 **Use Case**: Extract login credentials, API keys, or malware C2 commands from unencrypted traffic.\n\n---\n\n## 📊 **5. Key Analysis Tools (Statistics Menu)**\n\n| Tool | Use Case |\n|------|--------|\n| **Conversations** (`Statistics → Conversations`) | See top talkers (IP pairs, volume, duration) |\n| **Endpoints** | List all devices in the capture |\n| **Protocol Hierarchy** | % of traffic by protocol (e.g., 60% TLS, 20% DNS) |\n| **IO Graphs** | Visualize traffic spikes over time (great for DoS detection) |\n| **HTTP → Packet Counter** | Count HTTP requests/responses by code |\n| **Expert Info** (`Analyze → Expert Info`) | Warnings/errors (e.g., retransmissions, duplicate ACKs) |\n\n---\n\n## 🛡️ **6. Security & Forensics Tips**\n\n| Task | Technique |\n|------|---------|\n| **Detect Port Scans** | Look for sequential `tcp.port` attempts to one host with `tcp.flags.syn == 1` |\n| **Find Data Exfiltration** | Large outbound `frame.len` to unknown external IPs |\n| **Spot Malware C2** | Repeated DNS requests to strange domains (`dns.qry.name contains \"xyz123\"`) |\n| **Analyze TLS** | Check `tls.handshake.certificate` for suspicious domains |\n| **VLAN Traffic** | Use `vlan.id == 100` to isolate VLAN 100 traffic |\n| **Decrypt HTTPS (if you have key)** | Use SSL/TLS key log file: `Edit → Preferences → Protocols → TLS → (key log file)` |\n\n> 🔐 **Note**: You **cannot decrypt TLS** without the private key or session keys (e.g., from browser `SSLKEYLOGFILE`).\n\n---\n\n## 🧪 **Live Example: Find All Failed Login Attempts**\n\n1. Capture traffic on a web server.\n2. Apply display filter:\n   ```text\n   http.response.code == 401\n   ```\n3. Follow TCP stream on matching packets → inspect credentials in POST data (if unencrypted).\n\n> ✅ Works only on **HTTP** – not HTTPS (unless decrypted).\n\n---\n\n## 💾 **Save & Share**\n\n- **Export specific packets**: `File → Export Specified Packets`\n- **Export objects**: `File → Export Objects → HTTP` (grab images, files from web traffic!)\n- **Colorize packets**: Right-click packet → `Colorize Conversation` → easier visual tracking.\n\n---\n\n> 🌐 **Official Resources**:  \n> - Download: [https://www.wireshark.org](https://www.wireshark.org)  \n> - Display Filter Reference: [https://www.wireshark.org/docs/dfref/](https://www.wireshark.org/docs/dfref/)\n\n---\n\nLet me know if you’d like a **printable PDF version**, a **quick-reference one-pager**, or examples for **specific protocols** (e.g., DNS tunneling, SMB attacks, etc.)!"
      },
      {
        "title": "Live Wireshark Example",
        "content": "Absolutely! Here's a **live, hands-on example** using **Wireshark** to **detect suspicious outbound HTTP traffic** that could indicate data exfiltration or malware activity.\n\n> 🔍 **Scenario**: You're a junior security analyst reviewing traffic from a user’s workstation (`192.168.10.25`) after they reported slow performance and strange pop-ups. You suspect malware.\n\n---\n\n## 🧪 **Live Wireshark Example: Detecting Malicious HTTP Traffic**\n\n### ✅ Step 1: Start a Live Capture\n1. Open **Wireshark**.\n2. Select the active network interface (e.g., `Wi-Fi` or `eth0`).\n3. Click **Start** (or double-click the interface).\n\n> 💡 **Optional**: Use a **capture filter** to reduce noise:\n> ```\n> host 192.168.10.25\n> ```\n> This captures **only traffic to/from the suspicious host**.\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 2: Apply a Display Filter to Focus on HTTP\nIn the **filter bar**, type:\n```text\nhttp && ip.src == 192.168.10.25\n```\nThis shows **only HTTP requests sent by the user’s machine**.\n\n> 📌 You’ll see HTTP **GET/POST** requests to various domains.\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 3: Look for Anomalies\nScan the **Packet List** for:\n\n- Unusual domains (e.g., `xyz123-update-service.net`)\n- Large **POST** requests (possible data exfiltration)\n- Requests with strange **User-Agent** strings (e.g., `Python-urllib/3.x` on a regular user PC)\n\n🔍 **Example red flag**:\n- A POST to `http://malicious-domain.ru/upload.php` with 500 KB of data.\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 4: Inspect the Payload\n1. Right-click the suspicious packet.\n2. Select **Follow → HTTP Stream**.\n3. Wireshark reconstructs the full HTTP session.\n\n💡 In the stream, you might see:\n```http\nPOST /upload.php HTTP/1.1\nHost: malicious-domain.ru\nUser-Agent: Python-requests/2.28.0\nContent-Length: 512000\n\n{ \"user_files\": \"UEsDBBQACAgIAF...\", \"hostname\": \"WORKSTATION-01\" }\n```\n→ This looks like **stolen files being exfiltrated** (Base64-encoded ZIP).\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 5: Use Statistics to Confirm\nGo to **Statistics → Conversations → IPv4**:\n- Sort by **Bytes (A → B)**.\n- Is `192.168.10.25 → 93.184.216.34` (or unknown IP) sending **megabytes** while other traffic is minimal?\n\nAlso check:\n- **Statistics → HTTP → Requests** → Are there many requests to rare domains?\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 6: Save Evidence\n1. Right-click the malicious TCP stream → **Export Packet Bytes** (or export entire conversation).\n2. **File → Save As** → `malware_suspicion_20251219.pcapng`.\n\nNow you have forensic evidence for the IR team!\n\n---\n\n## 🛠️ Bonus: Quick Filters for Common Threats\n\n| Threat | Display Filter |\n|-------|----------------|\n| DNS Tunneling | `dns && dns.qry.name contains \"long-random-string\"` |\n| Internal Port Scan | `ip.src == 192.168.10.25 && tcp.flags.syn == 1 && tcp.flags.ack == 0` |\n| Unencrypted Passwords | `http contains \"password\"` |\n| Beaconing (C2) | `ip.src == 192.168.10.25 && frame.time_delta > 60` (regular intervals) |\n\n---\n\nThis is a **real-world workflow** used by SOC analysts daily.\n\nWant another live example? Try:\n- **Decrypting HTTPS with a key log**  \n- **Analyzing a phishing email attachment download**  \n- **Finding ARP spoofing attacks**\n\nJust ask!"
      },
      {
        "title": "Wireshark Example: Detecting ARP Spoofing",
        "content": "Absolutely! Here's **another live, hands-on Wireshark example**—this time focused on **detecting and analyzing an ARP spoofing (MITM) attack** on a local network.\n\n> 🔍 **Scenario**: Users on your internal network (`192.168.1.0/24`) are reporting intermittent connectivity and being redirected to fake login pages. You suspect an **ARP spoofing attack** (a common step in Man-in-the-Middle attacks).\n\n---\n\n## 🧪 **Live Wireshark Example: Detecting ARP Spoofing**\n\n### ✅ Step 1: Start Capture on the LAN Interface\n1. Open **Wireshark**.\n2. Select your **wired or Wi-Fi interface** (the one connected to the local network).\n3. Start capture **without a filter** (ARP is local and fast—you need full visibility).\n\n> ⚠️ **Tip**: Run this on a machine in the same subnet as the suspected attack.\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 2: Apply an ARP Display Filter\nIn the filter bar, type:\n```text\narp\n```\nNow you only see **ARP packets**—used to map IP addresses to MAC addresses.\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 3: Look for Duplicate MACs (Key Sign of Spoofing)\nIn the **Packet List**, watch for:\n- **Multiple IPs claiming the same MAC address**\n- **One MAC responding for many IPs**\n\n🔍 **Normal behavior**:\n- `192.168.1.1` → `aa:bb:cc:00:00:01` (router)\n- `192.168.1.10` → `dd:ee:ff:00:00:10` (user PC)\n\n🔍 **Malicious behavior**:\n- `192.168.1.1` → `11:22:33:aa:bb:cc` ← **attacker MAC**\n- `192.168.1.10` → `11:22:33:aa:bb:cc` ← **same attacker MAC!**\n\n→ This means the attacker is **impersonating both the router and the victim**.\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 4: Use Statistics to Confirm\nGo to:\n**Statistics → Endpoints → Ethernet**\n\nLook at the **MAC address column**:\n- Is one MAC (e.g., `11:22:33:aa:bb:cc`) associated with **multiple IP addresses**?\n- Does it appear far more than others?\n\n✅ **That’s your attacker.**\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 5: Identify the Attacker’s Machine\nNote the suspicious MAC (e.g., `11:22:33:aa:bb:cc`). Now:\n1. Filter by it:\n   ```text\n   eth.addr == 11:22:33:aa:bb:cc\n   ```\n2. Look at **all traffic** from that MAC.\n3. Check if it’s:\n   - Forwarding traffic (MITM),\n   - Running `dsniff`, `ettercap`, or `arpspoof`,\n   - Making unexpected DNS or HTTP requests.\n\nYou can also check your **DHCP server logs** or **switch CAM table** to find the physical port.\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 6: (Optional) Detect in Real Time with Alerts\nWhile capturing, go to:\n**Analyze → Expert Info → Notes/Warnings**\n\nLook for:\n- “Duplicate use of [IP] detected (MAC1 vs MAC2)”\n- “ARP ACK without preceding request”\n\nWireshark will **flag inconsistencies automatically**.\n\n---\n\n### 🛡️ Prevention Tip\n- Enable **DHCP Snooping + Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI)** on enterprise switches.\n- Use **static ARP entries** for critical devices (not scalable, but effective).\n- Deploy **ARP monitoring tools** like `arpwatch`.\n\n---\n\n## 📝 Summary: ARP Spoofing Indicators in Wireshark\n\n| Indicator | What to Look For |\n|--------|------------------|\n| **Duplicate MAC** | Same MAC mapped to multiple IPs |\n| **Excessive ARP** | One host sending ARP replies for many IPs |\n| **Gratuitous ARP** | Unsolicited ARP announcements (common in attacks) |\n| **Expert Warnings** | “Duplicate IP use” messages |\n\n---\n\n> ✅ **Real-World Impact**: This technique was used in attacks like **Ettercap MITM**, **Evil Twin**, and credential harvesting via fake HTTPS portals.\n\n---\n\nWant a **third live example**? Try one of these:\n- 📥 **Analyzing a phishing email: tracking a malicious download**\n- 🔐 **Decrypting TLS traffic using a browser’s SSLKEYLOGFILE**\n- 🚨 **Detecting DNS tunneling exfiltration**\n\nJust say the word!"
      },
      {
        "title": "Detecting DNS Tunneling",
        "content": "Absolutely! Here's **another live, realistic Wireshark example**—this time focused on **detecting DNS tunneling**, a common technique used by malware or insiders to **exfiltrate data or communicate with command-and-control (C2) servers** through DNS requests.\n\n> 🔍 **Scenario**: You’re monitoring internal network traffic and notice unusual DNS query volumes from a workstation (`10.10.20.35`). You suspect **DNS tunneling** (e.g., using tools like `dnscat2` or `iodine`).\n\n---\n\n## 🧪 **Live Wireshark Example: Detecting DNS Tunneling**\n\n### ✅ Step 1: Start Capture on Internal Network\n1. Open **Wireshark** on a machine that can see internal traffic (e.g., via SPAN port or local capture).\n2. Start capturing on the relevant interface.\n\n> 💡 Optional capture filter (if you know the suspicious host):  \n> ```\n> host 10.10.20.35\n> ```\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 2: Filter for DNS Traffic\nIn the display filter bar, type:\n```text\ndns\n```\nYou’ll now see only **DNS queries and responses**.\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 3: Look for Red Flags\nScan the **Info column** and **Packet Details** for these signs:\n\n| Red Flag | What It Looks Like |\n|--------|-------------------|\n| **Unusually long subdomains** | `aHR0cHM6Ly9leGFtcGxlLmNvbS9wYXlsb2Fk.dnsattacker.net` |\n| **High query rate** | Dozens of DNS queries per second from one host |\n| **Only TXT or NULL record types** | Malware often uses `TXT` to carry data |\n| **No repetition** | Legitimate apps reuse domains; tunneling uses unique, random names |\n\n🔍 **Example suspicious query**:\n```\nRandomString12345.data.exfil-malicious.com\n```\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 4: Analyze Query Patterns\n1. Right-click a suspicious DNS packet → **Follow → UDP Stream** (DNS runs over UDP port 53).\n2. Look at the full query sequence.\n\nYou might see:\n```\nGET /stage2 HTTP/1.1 → encoded as: c3RhZ2UyLmh0dHAuLi4u.dnsattacker.com\n```\n→ This is **base64 or hex data hidden in subdomains**.\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 5: Use Statistics to Quantify Anomaly\nGo to:\n**Statistics → DNS → Domain Name Analysis**\n\nLook for:\n- Domains with **very long labels** (>50 characters)\n- High **number of unique subdomains**\n- Domains **not seen before** in your environment\n\nAlso check:\n**Statistics → Conversations → UDP**\n- Is `10.10.20.35` making **hundreds of DNS requests** while other hosts make <10/min?\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 6: Confirm with a Custom Filter\nUse this filter to find long DNS queries:\n```text\ndns.qry.name matches \"\\\\.([a-z0-9]{30,})\\\\.\"\n```\n> This regex finds subdomains with **30+ alphanumeric characters**—a classic tunneling signature.\n\nOr find all `TXT` queries:\n```text\ndns.qry.type == 16\n```\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 7: Respond & Document\n- **Block the domain** at the firewall or DNS server (e.g., Pi-hole, Cisco Umbrella).\n- **Isolate the host** (`10.10.20.35`) for forensic analysis.\n- **Save the capture**: `File → Save As → dns_tunneling_evidence.pcapng`\n\n---\n\n## 🔒 Why This Matters\nDNS is often **allowed outbound** even in strict networks, making it a favorite for **data exfiltration** and **C2 communication**. Detecting it early stops:\n- Credential theft\n- Ransomware callbacks\n- Insider data leaks\n\n---\n\n## 🛠 Bonus: Common DNS Tunneling Tools (for detection reference)\n- `dnscat2`\n- `iodine`\n- `DNS2TCP`\n- `OzymanDNS`\n\nTheir traffic often includes:\n- Fixed domain suffix (e.g., `.yourdomain.net`)\n- Random or encoded prefixes\n- High entropy in subdomain names\n\n---\n\nWant **one more**? Here are quick ideas:\n- 🕵️ **Decrypt HTTPS using SSLKEYLOGFILE** (with Chrome & Wireshark)\n- 📤 **Trace a file download from an email link**\n- 🌐 **Analyze a SYN flood (DoS) attack**\n\nJust say which one!"
      },
      {
        "title": "Common Attacks Analyzed/Detected with Wireshark:",
        "content": "Wireshark itself **does not perform attacks**—it is a **passive network protocol analyzer** used for **monitoring, capturing, and inspecting traffic**.  \n\nHowever, Wireshark is commonly used to **detect, analyze, or investigate** the following **network-based attacks**:\n\n### 🔍 Common Attacks Analyzed/Detected with Wireshark:\n1. **ARP Spoofing / ARP Poisoning**  \n2. **DNS Tunneling**  \n3. **DNS Spoofing / Cache Poisoning**  \n4. **DHCP Starvation**  \n5. **Rogue DHCP Server**  \n6. **TCP SYN Flood (DoS)**  \n7. **TCP Session Hijacking**  \n8. **ICMP Flood / Smurf Attack**  \n9. **Port Scanning (SYN, FIN, XMAS scans)**  \n10. **Man-in-the-Middle (MITM) Attacks**  \n11. **Credential Sniffing (e.g., HTTP Basic Auth, FTP, Telnet)**  \n12. **Malware C2 (Command & Control) Communication**  \n13. **Data Exfiltration (via HTTP, DNS, ICMP, etc.)**  \n14. **SSL/TLS Stripping (indirectly via protocol downgrade)**  \n15. **VLAN Hopping (if 802.1Q tags are visible)**  \n16. **ZeroAccess / Botnet Traffic Patterns**  \n17. **Phishing / Malicious Payload Delivery (via HTTP)**  \n\n> ⚠️ **Remember**: Wireshark only **observes** traffic—it **cannot launch** these attacks. Tools like **Ettercap**, **nmap**, **hping3**, or **Scapy** are used to perform them.\n\nLet me know if you want detection filters for any of these!"
      },
      {
        "title": "MITM Attack via ARP Spoofing",
        "content": "Absolutely! Here's a **proper live example** of detecting and analyzing a **Man-in-the-Middle (MITM) attack** using **Wireshark**, based on a realistic scenario you might encounter in a security operations center (SOC) or penetration test lab.\n\n> ⚠️ **Important**: This example assumes you have **explicit permission** to monitor or test the network. Performing MITM without authorization is illegal.\n\n---\n\n## 🎯 **Live Wireshark Example: Detecting a MITM Attack via ARP Spoofing**\n\n### 🔧 **Scenario Setup**\n- **Network**: `192.168.1.0/24`\n- **Legitimate Gateway (Router)**:  \n  - IP: `192.168.1.1`  \n  - MAC: `aa:bb:cc:00:00:01`\n- **Victim Workstation**:  \n  - IP: `192.168.1.25`  \n  - MAC: `dd:ee:ff:00:00:25`\n- **Attacker Machine**:  \n  - IP: `192.168.1.50`  \n  - MAC: `11:22:33:aa:bb:cc`  \n  - Running `arpspoof` (from **dsniff** suite) to impersonate both gateway and victim.\n\n---\n\n## 🧪 **Step-by-Step Detection with Wireshark**\n\n### ✅ Step 1: Start Capture on the Local Network\nOn a monitoring machine (or the victim itself), open **Wireshark** and start capturing on the active interface (e.g., `eth0` or Wi-Fi).\n\n> 💡 No capture filter needed—ARP and traffic anomalies are fast and local.\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 2: Filter for ARP Traffic\nIn the **display filter bar**, type:\n```text\narp\n```\n\nObserve the ARP traffic in real time.\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 3: Identify Duplicate IP-to-MAC Mappings\nLook for **ARP announcements** like these:\n\n| Packet | Info |\n|-------|------|\n| #123 | `Who has 192.168.1.1? Tell 192.168.1.25` |\n| #124 | `192.168.1.1 is at 11:22:33:aa:bb:cc` ← ❌ **Wrong MAC!** |\n| #125 | `Who has 192.168.1.25? Tell 192.168.1.1` |\n| #126 | `192.168.1.25 is at 11:22:33:aa:bb:cc` ← ❌ **Attacker claiming to be victim!** |\n\n✅ **This is the smoking gun**:  \nThe **attacker’s MAC (`11:22:33:aa:bb:cc`)** is responding for **both** the gateway **and** the victim.\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 4: Confirm with Statistics\nGo to:  \n**Statistics → Endpoints → Ethernet**\n\nYou’ll see:\n- MAC `11:22:33:aa:bb:cc` associated with **two IPs**: `192.168.1.1` and `192.168.1.25`.\n- Legitimate MACs are **not responding** for their own IPs.\n\nThis violates normal network behavior → **clear MITM indicator**.\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 5: Observe Traffic Interception (Optional)\nNow remove the ARP filter and watch **HTTP** traffic:\n```text\nhttp && ip.src == 192.168.1.25\n```\n\nYou may see:\n- Victim browsing `http://bank.example/login`\n- But traffic is **routed through attacker** (visible in MAC layer)\n- If HTTP (not HTTPS), you can **see passwords in plaintext** in **Follow → TCP Stream**\n\n> 🔐 **Note**: With HTTPS, you’d see TLS handshake—but if the attacker uses a fake cert, you might see certificate warnings or unusual SNI names.\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Step 6: Expert Info Alert (Automatic Detection)\nGo to:  \n**Analyze → Expert Information → Warnings**\n\nWireshark may show:\n> “Duplicate use of 192.168.1.1 detected (aa:bb:cc:00:00:01 vs 11:22:33:aa:bb:cc)”\n\nThis is Wireshark **automatically flagging the MITM**.\n\n---\n\n## 🛡️ **How the Attack Was Performed (For Context)**\nOn the attacker machine:\n```bash\n# Spoof gateway to victim\narpspoof -i eth0 -t 192.168.1.25 192.168.1.1\n\n# Spoof victim to gateway (in another terminal)\narpspoof -i eth0 -t 192.168.1.1 192.168.1.25\n```\n\nWith IP forwarding enabled (`echo 1 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward`), the attacker **relays traffic silently**—making the MITM invisible to users.\n\n---\n\n## 📌 **Key Takeaways**\n- MITM via ARP spoofing is **common in local networks**.\n- Wireshark detects it via **MAC/IP inconsistencies**.\n- Always monitor for **duplicate ARP mappings** in sensitive environments.\n- Use **static ARP entries**, **DAI (Dynamic ARP Inspection)**, or **ARP monitoring tools** (e.g., `arpwatch`) to prevent it.\n\n---\n\nWould you like a **follow-up example** showing how to **decrypt HTTPS traffic in this MITM scenario** (e.g., with a rogue CA cert)?"
      },
      {
        "title": "How to analyze Wireshark",
        "content": "---\n\n# 🔥 LIVE ATTACK SCENARIOS + HOW TO ANALYZE (Wireshark)\n\nI’ll show **real attacks**, **what you see on the network**, and **how to detect them**.\n\n---\n\n## 1️⃣ HTTP CREDENTIAL THEFT (Clear-Text Login)\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nUser logs into website over **HTTP** (no HTTPS)\n\n### 🔍 Wireshark Detection\n\n**Filter**\n\n```\nhttp.request.method == \"POST\"\n```\n\n### 🧪 What to Look For\n\n```\nusername=admin&password=secret123\n```\n\n### 🛑 Problem\n\nCredentials stolen\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Force HTTPS\n* Enable HSTS\n\n---\n\n## 2️⃣ FTP PASSWORD SNIFFING\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nAttacker captures FTP login\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nftp\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n```\nUSER root\nPASS toor\n```\n\n### 🛑 Problem\n\nFTP sends passwords in plain text\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Use SFTP / FTPS\n\n---\n\n## 3️⃣ TELNET ROOT ACCESS HIJACK\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nAdmin logs in via Telnet\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\ntcp.port == 23\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n```\nlogin: root\nPassword: admin@123\n```\n\n### 🛑 Problem\n\nTelnet is insecure\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Disable Telnet\n* Use SSH\n\n---\n\n## 4️⃣ SMTP EMAIL PASSWORD LEAK\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nPassword sent via email\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nsmtp\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n```\nYour new password is: Welcome@123\n```\n\n### 🛑 Problem\n\nSensitive data in email\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Use encrypted mail (STARTTLS)\n* Never send passwords\n\n---\n\n## 5️⃣ REVERSE SHELL ATTACK (REAL HACKERS USE THIS)\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nAttacker gains shell on victim\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\ntcp.port == 1337\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n```\nwhoami\nroot\necho root:hacked123 | chpasswd\n```\n\n### 🛑 Problem\n\nFull system compromise\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Egress firewall rules\n* IDS/IPS\n* Endpoint monitoring\n\n---\n\n## 6️⃣ MALWARE FILE DOWNLOAD (HTTP)\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nVictim downloads malware\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n```\nGET /evil.exe\n```\n\n### 🛠️ Analysis\n\n* File → Export Objects → HTTP\n* Hash & scan file\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Block HTTP downloads\n* Use AV + proxy\n\n---\n\n## 7️⃣ DNS TUNNELING (DATA EXFILTRATION)\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nAttacker hides data in DNS\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\ndns\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* Very long domain names\n* High query rate\n\n### 🛑 Problem\n\nStealth data exfiltration\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* DNS logging\n* Block suspicious domains\n\n---\n\n## 8️⃣ ARP SPOOFING / MITM\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nAttacker becomes man-in-the-middle\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\narp\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* Same IP → multiple MACs\n\n### 🛑 Problem\n\nTraffic interception\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Dynamic ARP inspection\n* Static ARP\n\n---\n\n## 9️⃣ DDoS / SYN FLOOD\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nServer flooded with requests\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\ntcp.flags.syn == 1 && tcp.flags.ack == 0\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* Thousands of SYN packets\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Rate limiting\n* Firewall rules\n\n---\n\n## 🔎 REAL SOC ANALYSIS WORKFLOW\n\n### ✅ Step-by-Step\n\n1. Identify **protocol**\n2. Apply **filter**\n3. Follow **TCP stream**\n4. Look for **abnormal behavior**\n5. Extract **credentials/files**\n6. Identify **root cause**\n7. Apply **mitigation**\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 HOW TO THINK LIKE A SECURITY ANALYST\n\nAsk:\n\n* Is data encrypted?\n* Who initiated connection?\n* Is this normal behavior?\n* Is sensitive data exposed?\n\n---\n\nPerfect 👍\nBelow is a **DEEP-DIVE, REAL-WORLD SOC / Blue-Team GUIDE** with **MORE live attack scenarios**, **exact Wireshark filters**, **what the problem is**, **how to analyze**, and **how to fix it**.\nThis is the level used in **SOC interviews + real investigations**.\n\n---\n\n# 🔥 ADVANCED LIVE ATTACK SCENARIOS & WIRESHARK ANALYSIS\n\n---\n\n## 🔟 BRUTE-FORCE ATTACK (FTP / SSH)\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nAttacker tries many passwords\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nftp || ssh\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* Many `USER` / `PASS`\n* Many failed logins\n\n### 🚨 Problem\n\nAccount compromise risk\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Account lockout\n* Fail2Ban\n\n---\n\n## 1️⃣1️⃣ SQL INJECTION ATTACK\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nMalicious SQL in URL\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp contains \"select\" || http contains \"union\"\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n```\n?id=1 OR 1=1\n```\n\n### 🚨 Problem\n\nDatabase leak\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Input validation\n* WAF\n\n---\n\n## 1️⃣2️⃣ XSS (Cross-Site Scripting)\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nInject JavaScript\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp contains \"<script>\"\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n```\n<script>alert(1)</script>\n```\n\n### 🚨 Problem\n\nSession hijacking\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Output encoding\n* CSP headers\n\n---\n\n## 1️⃣3️⃣ COMMAND INJECTION\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nOS command execution\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp contains \";\"\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n```\n;cat /etc/passwd\n```\n\n### 🚨 Problem\n\nServer compromise\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Whitelisting inputs\n\n---\n\n## 1️⃣4️⃣ SMB CREDENTIAL CAPTURE\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nNTLM hash leakage\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nntlmssp\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* NTLM challenge-response\n\n### 🚨 Problem\n\nHash cracking\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Disable NTLM\n* SMB signing\n\n---\n\n## 1️⃣5️⃣ PASS-THE-HASH ATTACK\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nUsing NTLM hash instead of password\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nsmb || ntlmssp\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* No password entry\n* NTLM auth reuse\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Credential Guard\n\n---\n\n## 1️⃣6️⃣ RANSOMWARE COMMUNICATION\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nMalware contacting C2\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp || dns\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* Random domains\n* Base64 data\n\n### 🚨 Problem\n\nData encryption\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* DNS sinkhole\n* EDR\n\n---\n\n## 1️⃣7️⃣ DATA EXFILTRATION (HTTP POST)\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nSensitive data sent out\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp.request.method == \"POST\"\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* Large POST bodies\n* Unusual domains\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* DLP\n* Egress filtering\n\n---\n\n## 1️⃣8️⃣ MALICIOUS POWERSHELL (Windows)\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nEncoded PowerShell payload\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp contains \"powershell\"\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n```\n-EncodedCommand\n```\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* AMSI\n* Script logging\n\n---\n\n## 1️⃣9️⃣ DNS AMPLIFICATION ATTACK\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nDDoS using DNS\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\ndns && udp.length > 512\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* Large DNS responses\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Rate limiting\n\n---\n\n## 2️⃣0️⃣ MALICIOUS FILE DOWNLOAD (ZIP / EXE)\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nPayload download\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp.response.code == 200\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n```\nContent-Type: application/zip\n```\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Proxy inspection\n* Block EXE downloads\n\n---\nExcellent 👍\nNow I’ll go **EVEN DEEPER** — this is **REAL SOC / INCIDENT RESPONSE / BLUE-TEAM LEVEL** knowledge.\nI’ll give you **MORE live attack scenarios**, **what problem happens**, **how to detect it in Wireshark**, and **how analysts think**.\n\nRead slowly — this is **professional-grade content**.\n\n---\n\n# 🔥 ADVANCED LIVE ATTACK SCENARIOS (REAL WORLD)\n\n---\n\n## 2️⃣1️⃣ MAN-IN-THE-MIDDLE (MITM) – HTTP SESSION HIJACK\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nAttacker intercepts traffic on LAN (ARP spoofing)\n\n### 🔍 Wireshark Filters\n\n```\narp\nhttp\n```\n\n### 🧪 What You See\n\n* Same IP → different MAC\n* Session cookies in HTTP\n\n### 🚨 Problem\n\nSession hijack without password\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* HTTPS\n* ARP inspection\n\n---\n\n## 2️⃣2️⃣ COOKIE THEFT (WEB ATTACK)\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nAttacker steals session cookie\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp.cookie\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n```\nCookie: PHPSESSID=abc123\n```\n\n### 🚨 Problem\n\nAccount takeover\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Secure / HttpOnly cookies\n\n---\n\n## 2️⃣3️⃣ CREDENTIAL STUFFING (WEB)\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nAutomated login attempts\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp.request.method == \"POST\"\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* Many POST requests\n* Same IP, different users\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* CAPTCHA\n* Rate limiting\n\n---\n\n## 2️⃣4️⃣ SSH BRUTE FORCE\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nRepeated SSH attempts\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\ntcp.port == 22\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* Many SYN packets\n* Repeated failures\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Fail2Ban\n* Key-based auth\n\n---\n\n## 2️⃣5️⃣ BACKDOOR CONNECTION\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nMalware connects to attacker\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\ntcp.port == 4444 || tcp.port == 1337\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* Interactive shell traffic\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Egress firewall rules\n\n---\n\n## 2️⃣6️⃣ C2 (COMMAND & CONTROL) TRAFFIC\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nMalware beaconing\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\ndns || http\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* Repeated small connections\n* Regular time intervals\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* DNS monitoring\n* Threat intel blocking\n\n---\n\n## 2️⃣7️⃣ DNS DATA EXFILTRATION\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nData hidden in DNS queries\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\ndns && strlen(dns.qry.name) > 50\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* Base64-looking domains\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Block suspicious DNS\n\n---\n\n## 2️⃣8️⃣ POWERSHELL REVERSE SHELL (WINDOWS)\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nRemote PowerShell execution\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp contains \"powershell\"\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n```\nIEX(New-Object Net.WebClient)\n```\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* AMSI\n* Script logging\n\n---\n\n## 2️⃣9️⃣ SMB LATERAL MOVEMENT\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nMoving between machines\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nsmb || ntlmssp\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* NTLM auth reuse\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* Disable NTLM\n* SMB signing\n\n---\n\n## 3️⃣0️⃣ FILELESS MALWARE\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nMalware runs in memory\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp || dns\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n* No file download\n* Script payloads\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\n* EDR\n* Memory scanning\n\n---\nPerfect 👍\nLet’s go **even deeper** and make this feel like you’re sitting in a **real SOC lab** doing **live attack analysis**.\n\nI’ll give you **MORE scenarios**, **exact Wireshark steps**, **what attackers type**, and **how to spot it FAST**.\n\n---\n\n# 🔥 REAL-WORLD LIVE ATTACK ANALYSIS (ADVANCED)\n\n---\n\n## 3️⃣1️⃣ TELNET CREDENTIAL SNIFFING (CLEAR-TEXT)\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nUser logs in using Telnet (very insecure)\n\n### 🔍 Wireshark Filter\n\n```\ntelnet\n```\n\nor\n\n```\ntcp.port == 23\n```\n\n### 🧪 Steps\n\n1. Click a Telnet packet\n2. Right-click → **Follow → TCP Stream**\n3. Change **Show data as → ASCII**\n\n### 🔓 What You See\n\n```\nlogin: root\nPassword: toor123\n```\n\n### 🚨 Problem\n\nPasswords visible in plain text\n\n### 🔐 Fix\n\nDisable Telnet, use SSH\n\n---\n\n## 3️⃣2️⃣ FTP LOGIN PASSWORD LEAK\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nFTP login captured\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nftp || ftp-data\n```\n\n### 🧪 Evidence\n\n```\nUSER admin\nPASS admin@123\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3️⃣3️⃣ HTTP LOGIN PASSWORD CAPTURE\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nWebsite login over HTTP\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp.request.method == \"POST\"\n```\n\n### 🧪 Follow Stream → ASCII\n\n```\nusername=johndoe&password=hvb@nk123\n```\n\n### 🚨 Problem\n\nCredentials readable\n\n---\n\n## 3️⃣4️⃣ SMTP PASSWORD RESET EMAIL LEAK\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nEmail sent in clear text\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nsmtp\n```\n\n### 🧪 Follow Stream\n\n```\nYour new password is: Robert@2024\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3️⃣5️⃣ ZIP FILE PASSWORD FOUND VIA HTTP\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nZIP downloaded via HTTP\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp.response\n```\n\n### 🧪 Steps\n\n1. File → Export Objects → HTTP\n2. Save ZIP\n3. Open ZIP → password inside README\n\n### 🔓 Found\n\n```\nZIP password: secret@123\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3️⃣6️⃣ REVERSE SHELL PASSWORD CHANGE\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nAttacker connects on port 1337\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\ntcp.port == 1337\n```\n\n### 🧪 Follow Stream\n\n```\npasswd root\nNew password: r00t@1337\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3️⃣7️⃣ SQL INJECTION LOGIN BYPASS\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\n```\n' OR '1'='1\n```\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp.request\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3️⃣8️⃣ COMMAND INJECTION\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\n```\n; cat /etc/passwd\n```\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp contains \"cat\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3️⃣9️⃣ DATA EXFILTRATION VIA HTTP\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nSensitive data uploaded\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\nhttp.request.method == \"POST\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4️⃣0️⃣ DNS TUNNELING\n\n### 🧨 Attack\n\nStealth data exfil\n\n### 🔍 Filter\n\n```\ndns && strlen(dns.qry.name) > 60\n```\n\n---\n"
      }
